        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1962-10-08T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1962-10-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="314"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d314">
                <head>314. Memorandum from Sloan to Gilpatric, October 8<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d314fn1">Release of Cuban prisoners. Top Secret. 1 p. <gloss
                            target="#t_WNRC_1">WNRC</gloss>, RG 330, <gloss target="#t_OASD_1"
                            >OASD</gloss>/<gloss target="#t_ISA_1">ISA</gloss> Files: <gloss
                            target="#t_FRC_1">FRC</gloss> 65 A 3591, Cuba 1962, 00.1 (383.6
                        Cuba).</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-head" calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1962-10-08">October 8, 1962</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <pb facs="d314-1" n="1" type="facsimile" xml:id="d314-1"/>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Release of Cuban Prisoners</item>
                </list>
                <p>At a special meeting at State Saturday afternoon, <persName corresp="#p_MJA_1"
                        >John McCone</persName> advised the status of the <persName
                        corresp="#p_DJB_1">Donovan</persName> mission to Havana. Following the
                    meeting, contact was made with the President who approved the general
                    conclusions. One of these conclusions was that little or no attempt at secrecy
                    would be useful for more than a short time and that admission of the U.S.
                    Government backing of the exchange would be made (without details) upon press
                    inquiry.</p>
                <p>The quid pro quo is $50 million in drugs and medicines ($20 million cost to
                    Government) plus approximately $7 million collected by the Prisoners’ Committee,
                    in cash, to be transferred to the Royal Bank of Canada.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_DJB_1">Donovan</persName>, after flying to Miami yesterday
                    for some last minute instructions from Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MJA_1"
                        >McCone</persName>, was to return to Havana and fly out with the last group
                    of prisoners. A contract with Pan American had already been affected by <gloss
                        target="#t_CIA_1">CIA</gloss> to bring the prisoners out commencing today or
                    tomorrow if all goes well.</p>
                <p>I am available to brief you on further details of the meeting if you wish.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>Frank K. Sloan</signed>
                    <affiliation>Deputy Assistant Secretary</affiliation>
                </closer>
            </div>
